article.headline: Jackson sparks Vols to 13th straight win
article.linkText: Tennessee survives late scare from Auburn
article.story:
AUBURN, Ala. (AP) -- Tennessee's normally potent offense was
buried under a litany of missed shots and clanked free throws.

	   Nothing wrong with the defense, though.

	   Gwen Jackson scored 16 of her 20 points in the second half and
the third-ranked Lady Vols survived their biggest scare of the
Southeastern Conference season, beating Auburn 59-56 on Sunday with
a smothering defense.

	   "Auburn played with a lot more fire and intensity than we
did,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said. "I thought they were more
physical than we were. We won in spite of our poor shooting and
lack of rebounding and boxing out.''

	   The Lady Vols (22-3, 10-0) won their 13th straight game despite
hitting just two of six free throws in the final 58 seconds,
shooting 35 percent and making only 2-of-15 from 3-point range. It
was their worst offensive performance since a 76-55 loss to Duke on
Nov. 24.

	   Auburn (17-7, 5-5) had several chances to force overtime.
Natasha Brackett, who had 20 points, eight rebounds and six
assists, hit two 3-pointers in a 14-second span to make it 58-56
with 33 seconds left.

	   "We hung in there with one of the best teams in the country,''
Brackett said. "That shows our heart and determination. We were
just not able to pull it off in the end.''

	   Loree Moore then made one of two free throws eight seconds
later.

	   The Tigers couldn't get a good shot on the next sequence against
a smothering defense, with center Mandisa Stevenson firing an
airball from the top of the key with 9 seconds to play.

	   Le'Coe Willingham forced a turnover on the inbounds pass, giving
Auburn another shot. LaKeisha Johnson's 3-pointer from the left
wing bounced off the rim with 2 seconds remaining.

	   Moore missed two more free throws but Auburn couldn't get a
desperation shot to fall.

	   The Tigers still flirted with their first home victory over
Tennessee since 1991.

	   "This team learned they can play basketball at the highest
level with the energy they showed,'' Auburn coach Joe Ciampi said.
"It's just a matter of time before everything comes together.''

	   Moore finished with eight points, six assists and three steals
while Brittany Jackson had nine points off the bench.

	   Tennessee wasn't used to getting that kind of challenge in the
SEC this season, winning its first nine league games by an average
of 25 points and its last two by a combined 82.

	   The Lady Vols were the league's highest scoring team and ranked
fourth nationally in 3-point percentage. They did outrebound Auburn
45-35 and limited the Tigers to 34 percent shooting.

	   The Tigers scored the final seven points of the first half,
taking a 26-24 lead on Brackett's 3-pointer with 3 seconds left.

	   The Lady Vols had taken a 24-19 lead with their own 7-0 run with
2:05 left, but missed their final three shots.

	   Jackson played only seven minutes in the half, picking up two
quick fouls. She made the most of her time as a spectator.

	   "I was able to see how the outside wasn't open,'' she said. "I
tried to create an inside presence and let them decide if they
wanted to guard us inside or outside.

	   "In the second half, we took whatever was available.''
